      <div rendition="class:83225 maturity:83211" type="edition" xml:lang="san-Latn">
        <lg met="upajāti" n="1">
          <!--
Bhandarkar gives the metre as upendravajrā. Here and throughout this inscription I prefer to tag incomplete verses as upajāti, regardless of whether the extant lines are indra or upendra. Sohoni (cited by #Goyal_1980:51-52) believed the first three verses were about Samudra, Candra and Kumāragupta. Goyal disagrees with this because from svāmi-neyaḥ in l2 he concludes that the stanza is about a vassal. He believes that the inscription's author, Anantasena (l13) was the brother of KGI's wife, Anantadevī, on the strength of the Ananta in the name and the mention of svasā in l3, and that the first stanzas give the genealogy of Anantasena.
-->
          <l n="a">
            <lb n="1"/>
            <seg met="=+-++--+-+=">
              <gap quantity="11" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg>
          </l>
          <l n="b"><seg met="=+-++--+-+=">
              <gap quantity="11" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg> ḥ</l>
          <l n="c">nr̥-candra Indrānuja-tulya-vīryyo<!--
I suppose from nr̥candra that this stanza is about Candragupta II.
--></l>
          <l n="d">guṇair atulyaḥ <seg met="--+-+=">
              <gap quantity="6" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg> </l>
        </lg>
        <lg met="upajāti" n="2">
          <!--
The metre is defective, as pointed out by both Bhandarkar and Agrawala, in quarter c where svāmi must be pronounced sāmi in order to restore the preceding i to a short syllable.
-->
          <l n="a">
            <lb n="2"/>
            <seg met="=+-++--+-+=">
              <gap quantity="11" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg>
          </l>
          <l n="b">
            <seg met="=+-++--+-+=">
              <gap quantity="11" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg>
          </l>
          <l n="c"><unclear>ta</unclear>syāpi sūnur bhuvi svāmi-neyaḥ<!--
This stanza, then, would be about a son of CGII - can svāmin be an allusion to Kumāra? (attested in MW as one of his names).
--></l>
          <l n="d">khyātaḥ sva-kīrttyā <seg met="--+-+=">
              <gap quantity="6" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg> </l>
        </lg>
        <lg met="upajāti" n="3">
          <l n="a">
            <lb n="3"/>
            <seg met="=+-++--+-+=">
              <gap quantity="11" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg>
          </l>
          <l n="b">
            <seg met="=+-++--+-+=">
              <gap quantity="11" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg>
          </l>
          <l n="c"><unclear>sva</unclear>saiva yasyātula-vikrameṇa</l>
          <l n="d">kumāragup<unclear>t</unclear>e<unclear>na</unclear> <seg met="-+-+=">
              <gap quantity="5" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg> </l>
        </lg>
        <lg met="upajāti" n="4">
          <l n="a">
            <lb n="4"/>
            <seg met="=+-++--+-+=">
              <gap quantity="11" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg>
          </l>
          <l n="b">
            <seg met="=+-++--+-+=">
              <gap quantity="11" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg>
          </l>
          <l n="c">p<unclear>i</unclear>t<sic>r̥</sic>ṁś ca devāṁś ca hi havya-kavyaiḥ</l>
          <l n="d">sadānr̥śaṁsyādi <seg met="--+-+=">
              <gap quantity="6" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg><!--
Both Bhandarkar and Agrawala print sadā nr̥śaṁsyādi with a space. Surely it's sadā+ānr̥śaṁsya?
--></l>
        </lg>
        <lg met="vaṁśastha" n="5">
          <l n="a">
            <lb n="5"/>
            <seg met="-+-++--+-+-=">
              <gap quantity="12" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg>
          </l>
          <l n="b">
            <seg met="-+-++--+-+-=">
              <gap quantity="12" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg>
          </l>
          <l n="c"><supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->a</supplied>cīkarad deva-niketa-maṇḍalaṁ</l>
          <l n="d">kṣitāv an-aupamya <seg met="-+-+-=">
              <gap quantity="6" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg> </l>
        </lg>
        <lg met="vaṁśastha" n="6">
          <certainty locus="value" match="../@met"/>
          <!--
I cannot figure out the metre of this verse. Bhandarkar (following Fleet) proposes gīti for this and the following stanza; Sircar says "a metre of the jāti type"; Agrawala says both. I'm unable to work out any way the extant text could be fitted to gīti (the line breakups presented by Agrawala certainly seem wrong; Bhandarkar does no bother to show line structure), and I'm quite certain the next verse is a praharṣiṇī. I would assume that this is either a vaṁśastha like the preceding stanza, or a praharṣiṇī like the next one. The pattern does not fit praharṣiṇī, but may fit vaṁśastha if some readings are changed. Need to return to this - either mark it up as prose or figure out a plausible line breakup. Upendravajrā/upajāti is also a possibility.
-->
          <l n="a">
            <lb n="6"/>
            <seg met="-+-++--+-+-=">
              <gap quantity="12" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg>
          </l>
          <l n="b">
            <seg met="-+-++--+-+-=">
              <gap quantity="12" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg>
          </l>
          <l n="c"><unclear cert="low">baṭe</unclear> kila stambha-varocchr<sic>i</sic>ya-prabhā<!--
Agrawala reads a tentative ṇa instead of Bhandarkar's tentative baṭe. I can see both if I really want to, but cannot vote confidently for either. The reading baṭe fits my supposition about the metre, though if this is part of the same name that occurs later, it would be surprising to see it split at the half-verse. I think it would also be possible to read śaila or śilā instead of kila. Compare the long stem of śa in ānr̥śaṁsya above.
--></l>
          <l n="d">setu maṇḍa <gap extent="unknown" reason="illegible" unit="character"/> <supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->||</supplied><!--
Instead of setu, I could imagine site (compare the long stem of t in ānata in the next line), and then we could read prabhāsite which would then begin the final quarter, but leave the previous quarter hypometrical.
--></l>
        </lg>
        <lg met="praharṣiṇī" n="7">
          <certainty locus="value" match="../@met"/>
          <!--
As for the previous verse, Bhandarkar (following Fleet) proposes gīti for this and the following stanza; Sircar says "a metre of the jāti type"; Agrawala says both. I'm unable to work out any way the extant text could be fitted to gīti, and I'm quite certain this is a praharṣiṇī.
-->
          <l n="a">
            <lb n="7"/>
            <seg met="+++----+-+-+=">
              <gap quantity="13" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg>
          </l>
          <l n="b"><seg met="+++----+-+-+">
              <gap quantity="12" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg> <unclear>bhi</unclear>r </l>
          <l enjamb="yes" n="c">vr̥kṣāṇāṁ kusuma-bhar-ānat-āgra-<unclear cert="low">śuṁga</unclear><!--
Perhaps śr̥ṁga is more likely than śuṁga; the ga is problematic in either case.
--></l>
          <l n="d">-vyālamba-stavaka <seg met="-+-+-+=">
              <gap quantity="7" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg> </l>
        </lg>
        <lg met="upajāti" n="8">
          <l n="a">
            <lb n="8"/>
            <seg met="=+-++--+-+=">
              <gap quantity="11" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg>
          </l>
          <l n="b">
            <seg met="=+-++--+-+=">
              <gap quantity="11" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg>
          </l>
          <l enjamb="yes" n="c">bhadrāryyayā bhāti gr̥haṁ navābhra</l>
          <l n="d">-
nirmmoka-nirmu<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->kta</supplied><seg met="-+-+=">
              <gap quantity="5" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg> </l>
        </lg>
        <lg met="upajāti" n="9">
          <l n="a">
            <lb n="9"/>
            <seg met="=+-++--+-+=">
              <gap quantity="11" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg>
          </l>
          <l n="b">
            <seg met="=+-++--+-+=">
              <gap quantity="11" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg>
          </l>
          <l n="c">skanda-pradhānair bhuvi mātr̥bhiś ca</l>
          <l n="d">lokān <unclear>sa</unclear> <unclear cert="low">suṣya</unclear><seg met="--+-+=">
              <gap quantity="6" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg><!--
For the end, Agrawala (Sircar?) reads samya[#k], ignoring the strong and curled bottom mātrā of the first character in this string. Perhaps best to read lokān sa muṁcaty, if the subscript ya belongs to the character following what others have seen as the left part of ṣa and what I see as more like ca.
--></l>
        </lg>
        <lg met="upajāti" n="10">
          <l n="a">
            <lb n="10"/>
            <seg met="=+-++--+-+=">
              <gap quantity="11" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg>
          </l>
          <l n="b">
            <seg met="=+-++--+-+=">
              <gap quantity="11" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg>
          </l>
          <l n="c"><seg met="=+-">
              <gap quantity="3" reason="lost" unit="character"/>
            </seg> yūpocchrayam eva cakkre</l>
          <l n="d">bhadrāryyādi <gap extent="unknown" reason="lost" unit="character"/><!--
Bhandarkar and Agrawala both construe verse 10 as ending at cakkre, taking bhadrāryyādi as the first word of prose following it. This would, however, be very strange: we'd expect the extant portion to commence around the beginning of the third, not fourth quarter of an upajāti stanza, as in all lines above. Assuming I'm right, bhadrāryyādi would be unmetrical, so we'd better read bhadrāryya-di or, even more likely once we've dispensed with ādi, bhadrāryya-dī.
--></l>
        </lg>
        <p><lb n="11"/><gap extent="unknown" reason="lost" unit="character"/> nd<unclear cert="low">r</unclear>aguptabaṭe A<sic>n</sic>śāni <num value="35"><g type="numeral">30</g> 5</num> <unclear>tā</unclear>mra<unclear cert="low">kaṭākuḥ kala</unclear> <gap extent="unknown" reason="lost" unit="character"/> <lb n="12"/><gap extent="unknown" reason="lost" unit="character"/> pituḥ sva-mātur yyady asti hi duṣkr̥taṁ bhajatu tane <gap extent="unknown" reason="lost" unit="character"/> <lb n="13"/><gap extent="unknown" reason="lost" unit="character"/> k-āgrahāre Anśāni <num value="3">3</num> Anantasenenopa <gap extent="unknown" reason="lost" unit="character"/><!--
Bhandarkar (following Fleet) conjecturally reads [#ska]ndaguptabaṭe. Majumdar notes that this is more likely ndra than nda, so perhaps indraguptabaṭa or candraguptabaṭa. Agrawala reads [#ca]ndraguptabaṭe and credits Majumdar and Jagannath. I agree that ndra is quite likely.
--><!--
#Goyal_1980 proposes to read/restore yady asti hi sukr̥taṁ bhavatu tatre... on the basis of Mitra's reading "sukutaṁ" and on the assumption that talking about "the bad deeds of one's own parents is unthinkable".
--></p>
